body_html:
Something funny happened, I used to run my Tensorflow on Linux and Unix system. Today was my first time to install and run on a window device.....and I ran into a problem with retraining a model as well. But it's slightly different. It kept complaining about flower_photos not found. As if the directory isn't there.....but I made sure it is........not sure what's the problem still.....
…
On 23 Feb 2018 20:27, "clark ho" ***@***.***> wrote: For me anyway the jpeg looked like it was correct, the format looked correct. I checked everything,I even open it to view the image, everything looked right, but for some reason for me when the images is moved from a folder to another some transfer method causes jpeg to loss some bits from it's base64 string.......no idea why. When I compared the Actual base64 then I saw the string was slightly different.......then I tried a different transfer method, when the base64 string is 100% the same.....then it worked. No idea why, I think the Tensorflow has to mount the image into the image parser in C++ then read it, so basically the system couldn't mount the image to parse and gave that error, if you guys base64 is correct or file format is correct, maybe take a look at the log to see if the image is even getting read correctly. body_text:
Something funny happened, I used to run my Tensorflow on Linux and Unix
system. Today was my first time to install and run on a window
device.....and I ran into a problem with retraining a model as well. But
it's slightly different. It kept complaining about flower_photos not found.
As if the directory isn't there.....but I made sure it is........not sure
what's the problem still.....
…
On 23 Feb 2018 20:27, "clark ho" ***@***.***> wrote:
 For me anyway the jpeg looked like it was correct, the format looked
 correct. I checked everything,I even open it to view the image, everything
 looked right, but for some reason for me when the images is moved from a
 folder to another some transfer method causes jpeg to loss some bits from
 it's base64 string.......no idea why. When I compared the Actual base64
 then I saw the string was slightly different.......then I tried a different
 transfer method, when the base64 string is 100% the same.....then it
 worked. No idea why, I think the Tensorflow has to mount the image into the
 image parser in C++ then read it, so basically the system couldn't mount
 the image to parse and gave that error, if you guys base64 is correct or
 file format is correct, maybe take a look at the log to see if the image is
 even getting read correctly.
